{
  "texts": [
    "Contrastive Learning of SSL4NS-TDAnother common theme of the advancements is to learn robust representations via different views or corruptions of the same input, which is achieved by maximizing similarities between similar instances and pulling over instances that are dissimilar.",
    "With the success of generating views in computer vision (CV) and masking tokens in natural language processing (NLP) (Jaiswal et al, 2020), contrastive learning has been attempted in tabular applications to learn effective and generic task-agnostic representations.",
    "Formally, the formula of contrastive learning can be generally defined as:L contrastive = ϕ(h i, h + i, h - j),(3)h i = e(x i); h + i = e(x + i); h - j = e(x - j), (4)where ϕ is a similarity function that compares similarities between the anchor (h i), positive (h + i), and negative (h - i) instances.",
    "A positive instance is a variant of the anchor by augmentation methods (e.g., partial features of the anchor), and a negative instance is often sampled from the other instances.",
    "Positive pairs represent two similar instances, while negative pairs represent two dissimilar instances."
  ]
}